                    <h2>Passing the Guard</h2>
                    <p>
                        Guard passing is critical for gaining a dominant position in BJJ. Whether it's a knee slice pass or a torreando pass, mastering these techniques lets you transition from a neutral position into side control, mount, or other advantageous positions, keeping your opponent on the defensive.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Learn more about guard passing:
                        <a href="https://www.bjjscout.com/" target="_blank">BJJ Scout</a>
                    </p>
                </RadzenCard>
                <RadzenCard Style="background-color: var(--rz-danger-lighter); padding: 20px; grid-column: span 4;">
                    <h2>The Role of Submissions in BJJ</h2>
                    <p>
                        Submissions are the essence of BJJ. They allow you to end a fight or match without causing serious harm to your opponent. Techniques like the armbar, triangle choke, and rear-naked choke can be used to control and submit opponents by applying joint locks or chokes.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Learn more about submissions:
                        <a href="https://www.bjjheroes.com/" target="_blank">BJJ Heroes</a>
                    </p>
                </RadzenCard>
            </RadzenStack>
            <RadzenCard Style="background-color: var(--rz-warning-lighter); padding: 20px; grid-column: span 3;">
                <h2>The Guard: Your Most Powerful Weapon</h2>
                <p>
                    The guard is essential in BJJ, allowing you to control opponents from the bottom position. There are many types of guards, such as the closed guard, open guard, and spider guard, all offering unique ways to neutralize an attack and prepare submissions.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Learn more about guard techniques:
                    <a href="https://www.grapplersguide.com/" target="_blank">Grapplers Guide</a>
                </p>
            </RadzenCard>
