    <RadzenCard Style="background-color: var(--rz-primary-lighter); padding: 20px; grid-column: span 6;">
        <h2>The Origins of Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu</h2>
        <p>
            Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu (BJJ) was born in the early 20th century when Mitsuyo Maeda, a Judo master, brought grappling to Brazil. The Gracie family modified these techniques to focus on ground fighting and submissions, creating the BJJ system we know today. Over the years, BJJ has grown into an internationally respected martial art.
        </p>
        <p>
            Learn more about BJJ's history:
            <a href="https://www.gracieuniversity.com/" target="_blank">Gracie University</a>
        </p>
    </RadzenCard>
</RadzenStack>

<RadzenCard Style="background-color: var(--rz-info-lighter); padding: 20px; grid-column: span 4;">
    <h2>Gi vs. No-Gi Jiu-Jitsu</h2>
    <p>
        BJJ can be practiced with the gi (kimono) or without it. Gi BJJ focuses on grip-based techniques, while no-gi relies on body control and speed. Both styles have their own challenges and benefits, and training in both can develop a well-rounded grappling skill set.
    </p>
    <p>
        Learn more:
        <a href="https://www.jiujitsutimes.com/" target="_blank">Jiu Jitsu Times</a>
    </p>
</RadzenCard>
